		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message32944699"><!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>Detective said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br>To me, Hyouka is one of the most unbearable anime of all time. Visually exciting for a slice-of-life that takes place mostly in one room, the characters are what make this anime take a nosedive for me. The lead male seems like a masturbatory recreation of Kyon, and the lead female is so impossibly simplistic it makes the mystery aspect practically disappear. <!--quote--></div><br />
Strong disagree about Oreki - there are similarities to Kyon, yes, and while he's not Kyon-tier, he's still excellent for a variety of reasons and his development is one of the more beautiful things I've seen in anime. I find the tone and pacing of Hyouka seems attuned to Oreki himself. Once you get over his silly catchphrase, it becomes apparent that he has issues with social interaction and a poor attitude to life.<br />
<br />
<div class="quotetext">When a &quot;mystery&quot; arises you know our genius-in-disguise will supersleuth it out. He'll manage to trigger a series of impossible conclusions with the help of the only two supporting cast members. It's just frustrating to see Hyouka tagged as a mystery when it is certainly not. Clues are never more meaningful than their face value of being clues by definition. They simply lead the cast towards the inevitability that the mystery will be solved. For me, mystery is more than that. A good mystery reveals as much about the detective as it does about the narrative. That's where Hyouka falls flat. I really do enjoy the premise, but the execution makes me think KyoAni made this anime for I don't know... something... else...<!--quote--></div><br />
Reading this, I feel you're saying one of the reasons the show is bad is because it's not what you'd expect from something that's supposed to be a mystery. I see the mysteries in Hyouka as merely a tool to explore Oreki and to allow Chitanda to start to change him, make him come out of his shell.<br />
Certainly, a lot of the smaller mysteries don't bring much to the table, and for mystery fans I'm sure they're pretty dull. But with, say, the school festival mystery, the show really begins to shine, and this is where we really start to dig deep into Oreki's life attitude and social problems.<br />
The ending is not nearly as cathartic as I'd like, but it does indicate the significant development that has taken place. It is very subtle, but when you realise it's happening, it is beautiful...<br />
<br />
<!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>einonymous said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br><br />
Yeah, the art is great, but I've seen plenty more anime with art just as good, or better. Besides, the art was just the typical KyoAni moe stuff, with transparent-like backgrounds, again, typical of KyoAni. <!--quote--></div><br />
I would argue that it has among the best/animation art of any tv series I've seen. Takemoto Yasuhiro is a master director, and his use of depth and lighting adds so much to the atmosphere and unique feel of the show. Out of curiosity - what are the shows you consider to have better animation? Stuff like Yuasa Masaaki's shows and the like can't really be compared to this though, they are so vastly different. I'd say something like Mushishi is of a similar quality as Hyouka though.<br />
But seriously, stuff like that scene in ep 1 with the vines and flowers entangling Oreki, and that scene later in the show where all the chibi Chintanda's surround Oreki with the &quot;kininarimasu, kininarimasu, etc etc&quot; - these are amazing.</div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
